Another way to develop the graph of h\left(x \right) is to study one cycle of f\left(x \right) = \sin \left(x \right).  Since  incorporates no shifts or stretches,  completes one cycle on the interval 0 \le x \le 2\pi.  In the function h\left(x \right) , the argument of sine is \left(2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \right).   Since f\left(x \right) = \sin \left(x \right) completes one cycle when its argument, x, varies from 0 to 2\pi, h\left(x \right) = \sin \left(2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \right) completes one cycle when its argument 2x - \frac{\pi}{4}, varies from 0 to 2\pi.  Thus, h completes one cycle when 0 \le 0 2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \le 2\pi.  Solve this inequality for x as follows:

            0 \le 2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \le 2\pi
            \frac{\pi}{4} \le 2x \le \frac{9\pi}{4}
            \frac{\pi}{8} \le 2x \le \frac{9\pi}{8}

          Therefore, h\left(x \right) = \sin \left(2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \right) completes one cycle in the interval \frac{\pi}{8} \le 2x \le \frac{9\pi}{8}.  This interval is consistent with the graph shown in .  The shape of the graph on the interval \frac{\pi}{8} \le 2x \le \frac{9\pi}{8} is repeated every \pi units sinceh\left(x \right) = \sin \left(2x - \frac{\pi}{4} \right) has a period of \pi.
